| state t+1 | **Title: The Promise Vendor: A Rational Choice Model of Entrepreneurial Overpromise Abstract:** Entrepreneurial ventures often engage in "overpromising," a behavior widely viewed through the lens of cognitive bias. We challenge this view by developing a rational choice model to explain when and by how much an entrepreneur should promise *before* securing the resources to deliver. We extend the classic newsvendor model in two fundamental ways: (1) we define time-symmetric underage and overage costs (`Cu`, `Co`) for decisions made under two-sided commitment uncertainty (from both customers and resource partners); and (2) we introduce a "matching value" (`V`), representing the unique prize of successfully aligning these commitments. Our model yields a closed-form solution for the optimal promise level (`q*`), demonstrating that overpromising is a rational strategy when the opportunity cost of a missed sale (`Cu`) is high relative to the cost of a broken promise (`Co`). Counter-intuitively, our analysis reveals that the matching value (`V`) acts as a strategic moderator, not a simple accelerant of ambition. For ventures facing high opportunity costs (`Cu > Co`), a larger prize (`V`) dampens the tendency to overpromise, enforcing discipline. Conversely, for ventures facing high failure costs (`Co > Cu`), `V` provides the necessary incentive to undertake calculated risks. Theoretically, we contribute a unified framework that reframes apparent entrepreneurial bias as a predictable output of a firm's strategic context. Managerially, we introduce the duality of the proactive "Promise Vendor," who acts to shape the future, and the reactive "News Vendor," who optimizes based on the past. This distinction provides a formal language for allocating resources between opportunity creation and operational efficiency. **Keywords:** Entrepreneurship, Newsvendor Model, Promise, Overpromise, Decision Theory, Resource Allocation, Strategic Duality. |

| state t+1 | **ABSTRACT** Entrepreneurs face stark stakeholder heterogeneity (A): each partner arrives with private quality beliefs (A1) while moving at distinct action tempos (A2). We address this phenomenon by fusing discrete‚Äêchoice commitment logic with a two uncertainty source **newsvendor** into a **Bayesian decision‚Äìoperations framework** (D). Our model (i) forecasts commitment probabilities via a quality-driven commitment prediction model (G1) and (ii) aligns decision tempos through a clockspeed synchronization model (G2). Our framework balances predicted oversell and under-deliver risk. This tradeoff is analyzed under different settings of quality and action tempos of resource partners versus customers. By (i) unifying heterogeneous beliefs (A1) and tempos (A2) into a single response surface (G12) and (ii) converting that surface into an actionable coordination toolkit, our framework empowers founders to flexibly push quality-driven tempos or pull tempo-driven quality (C12).  **LIT REVIEW PLAN** **Stream (Literature Focus)** **Weight** **Focus & Key Works (with citation)** **Current Gap** üü™ **Heterogeneity Dynamics** (priors vary, clocks diverge) Medium Industries and stakeholders often operate at different "clockspeeds" (rates of evolution). Fine‚Äôs *Clockspeed* theory posits that firms must adapt to varying industry clockspeeds; likewise, entrepreneurs hold unique prior beliefs that drive divergent strategic actions. Recent Bayesian models formalize how founders update these heterogeneous priors through theory-driven search and experimentation. Lack of frameworks incorporating differing stakeholder priors and time horizons into venture decision models ‚Äì current research treats heterogeneous beliefs and pacing misalignment conceptually but offers no integrated solution. üü© **Managing Commitment Under Uncertainty** High Entrepreneurs must balance irreversible commitments with flexibility in unpredictable environments. Pich, Loch & De Meyer (2002) identify project strategies (**instructionism** vs **learning**) selected based on uncertainty type, highlighting when to stick to plans or adapt. Thomke & Bell (2001) derive optimal sequential testing policies in R\&D to time commitments for risk mitigation. Behavioral experiments reveal biases in such decisions (e.g. order quantities pulled toward mean demand), underscoring the difficulty of optimal commitment under risk. No unified logic linking entrepreneurs‚Äô discrete commitment choices with operational models ‚Äì existing work on real options and bias lacks a prescriptive ‚Äúwhen/how to commit‚Äù rule tailored to entrepreneurial contexts. üüß **Integrated Quality‚ÄìTempo Response Models** Medium Quality (thoroughness) and tempo (speed) must be coordinated in venture operations. Higher service quality often comes at the expense of speed, creating a need for models that jointly optimize these trade-offs. Emerging **prescriptive analytics** frameworks bridge prediction and action: Bertsimas & Kallus (2020) integrate machine learning forecasts with optimization for decision-making; Elmachtoub & Grigas (2022) embed predictive models directly into planning (‚Äúsmart predict-then-optimize‚Äù). In operations, multi-stage newsvendor formulations (e.g. Van Mieghem & Rudi 2002\) allow flexible capacity allocation under uncertainty, aiming to maintain service quality while responding quickly to demand changes. Siloed treatment of quality vs. speed ‚Äì few existing models co-optimize product/service quality and delivery tempo. Lacks a Bayesian coordination toolkit to help entrepreneurs dynamically balance improving quality with expediting time-to-market. üü• **Push‚ÄìPull Decision Rules & Duality** High Supply chain research has established the **push‚Äìpull** dichotomy as a core strategic decision. Fisher‚Äôs seminal framework matched efficient *push* systems to stable products and responsive *pull* systems to innovative products. The **decoupling point** (push‚Äìpull boundary) delineates stages of speculative production vs. reactive fulfillment, and extensive studies (e.g. Olhager 2010\) examine how its placement affects performance. Later work (Lee 2004\) reframed push‚Äìpull into dynamic capabilities of Agility, Adaptability, and Alignment. However, guidance for startups remains scattered, with no integrated ‚Äúdual‚Äù strategy prescribing how to combine push and pull approaches. Absence of a unified push‚Äìpull strategy for new ventures ‚Äì existing literature provides either/or criteria but no dual push‚Äìpull rule. Entrepreneurs lack a prescriptive guideline to simultaneously leverage efficient planning (push) and agile response (pull) in tandem.  |
